\begin_layout Definition
Notation: (a) 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi\in\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

 would typically represent the quantum mechanical state of the system (assumed
 pure), residing in the Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}$
\end_inset

, (b) 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mathcal{H}}$
\end_inset

 is defined to mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{H}\otimes\mathcal{H}^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

, (c) 
\begin_inset Formula $[\mathcal{H}]$
\end_inset

 is defined to mean 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mathcal{H},\,\mathbb{R}^{\otimes})$
\end_inset

, which represents the state of the system including hidden variables, (d)
 
\begin_inset Formula $[\psi]\in[\mathcal{H}]$
\end_inset

 will represent the state of the system, including hidden variables, (e)
 a prediction map is 
\begin_inset Formula $m:\hat{\mathcal{H}},[\mathcal{H}]\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, (f) a sequence map is 
\begin_inset Formula $s:\hat{\mathcal{H}},[\mathcal{H}],\mathbb{R}\to[\mathcal{H}]$
\end_inset

, (g) the set of all experimental setups is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{E}$
\end_inset

, (h) a setup map is 
\begin_inset Formula $e:\hat{\mathcal{H}}\to\mathcal{E}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition to the notation, we use the following definition of non-contextualit
y.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
A theory is non-contextual, if it provides a map 
\begin_inset Formula $m:\hat{\mathcal{H}},[\mathcal{H}]\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 to explain measurement outcomes.
 A theory which is not non-contextual is contextual.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
Prediction maps are non-contextual.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the literature broader definitions have been suggested which declare
 a larger set of theories as non-contextual.
 For our purposes however, this restricted definition will suffice.
 The term contextual is used to suggest that the value an operator takes
 might depend on which other compatible observable it is measured with.
 Since quantum mechanics (QM) yields deterministic results only in specific
 situations, it is imperative to analyse the meaning of contextuality by
 `completing' QM.
 Hidden variable theories do precisely this and we have at our disposal
 the heretic theory of Bohm.
 Circumventing the details of the theory, we note its salient feature; with
 each particle, one associates precisely defined 
\begin_inset Formula $(q,p)$
\end_inset

 and a wavefunction 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

.
 Consequently, the outcomes of all experiment are predictable, granted the
 initial conditions of the system and the apparatus are known (the `hidden
 variables').
 The essence of Bohmian Mechanics relevant here can be captured by the following
 theorem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset Formula $\exists$
\end_inset

 a (Bohmian) map 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{B}:\hat{\mathcal{H}},[\mathcal{H}],\mathcal{E}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, and a sequence map 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, s.t.
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{B}$
\end_inset

 & 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 are assumed to describe the outcomes of measurements & the resultant state
 respectively, then they are consistent with all predictions of QM.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Observe that given a Stern-Gerlach setup and the initial conditions (position
 & wavefunction of the particle), according to the theorem, Bohmian mechanics
 can predict the value of the spin (say 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\sigma}_{z}$
\end_inset

) of the particle.
 Assume that the state of the particle was 
\begin_inset Formula $(\left|0\right\rangle +\left|1\right\rangle )/\sqrt{2}$
\end_inset

 and that the measurement outcome was spin up.
 Interestingly, it can be shown 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Detlef"

\end_inset

 that if the direction of the magnetic field gradient is flipped while everythin
g else is unchanged, the measurement outcome will now be spin down.
 This emphasises the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{B}$
\end_inset

 is not a prediction map.
 More importantly it entails that 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{B}$
\end_inset

 is contextual.
 It must be stressed, however, that the contextuality in this case is not
 a statement about the context in terms of compatible observables.
 Here no two observables are compatible (excluding identity).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Non-Multiplicativity: An alternative to Contextuality
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One can show 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "KochenSpecker"

\end_inset

 that under reasonable assumptions, no non-contextual theory can explain
 all predictions of QM.
 We re-state these results and show that nowhere does contextuality appear
 to be a logical necessity.
 Instead we note that non-contextual theories with certain properties, we
 call 
\emph on
multiplicativity
\emph default
 are incompatible with QM.
 Viewed from this perspective, non-
\emph on
multiplicativity
\emph default
 is the non-classical alternative to contextuality in QM.
 Precise definitions of this and a related property 
\emph on
sequential multiplicativity
\emph default
, are given below.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
A prediction map 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
multiplicative 
\emph default
iff 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m(f(\hat{B}_{1},\hat{B}_{2},\dots\hat{B}_{N}),[\psi])=f(m(\hat{B}_{1},[\psi]),m(\hat{B}_{2},[\psi]),\dots m(\hat{B}_{N},[\psi])),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}_{i}\in\hat{\mathcal{H}}$
\end_inset

 are arbitrary mutually commuting observables, 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\hat{\mathcal{H}}^{\otimes N}\to\mathcal{\hat{H}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $[\psi]\in[\mathcal{H}]$
\end_inset

.
 A non-
\emph on
multiplicative
\emph default
 map is one that is not multiplicative.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that if 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is taken to represent the measurement outcome (in QM), then for states
 of the system which are simultaneous eigenkets of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}_{i}$
\end_inset

s, 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 must clearly be multiplicative.
 It is, however, not obvious that this property must always hold.
 To motivate this, consider the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|11\right\rangle :=\left|1\right\rangle \otimes\left|1\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 written in the computational basis, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}_{1}=\hat{\sigma}_{x}\otimes\hat{\sigma}_{x}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}_{2}=\hat{\sigma}_{y}\otimes\hat{\sigma}_{y}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{C}=\hat{B}_{1}\hat{B}_{2}=-\hat{\sigma}_{z}\otimes\hat{\sigma}_{z}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $m(\hat{C})=-1$
\end_inset

 while 
\begin_inset Formula $m(\hat{B}_{1})=\pm1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m(\hat{B}_{2})=\pm1$
\end_inset

, independently, according to QM, with probability half.
 Contrary to this, from a quick computation, it is clear that if one first
 measures 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and subsequently measures 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}_{2}$
\end_inset

, then the product of the results must be 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

.
 This is consistent with measuring 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{C}$
\end_inset

.
 To capture this property we define 
\emph on
sequential multiplicativity
\emph default
 as follows.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
A prediction map 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is 
\emph on
sequentially multiplicative 
\emph default
for a given sequence map 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, iff 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m(f(\hat{B}_{1},\hat{B}_{2},\dots\hat{B}_{N}),[\psi_{1}])=f(m(\hat{B}_{1},[\psi_{k_{1}}]),m(\hat{B}_{2},[\psi_{k_{2}}]),\dots,m(\hat{B}_{N},[\psi_{k_{N}}])),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{k}=(k_{1},k_{2},\dots,k_{N})\in\{(1,2,3\dots N),(2,1,3\dots N)+\text{ permutations, making }N!\text{ terms}\}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}_{i}\in\hat{\mathcal{H}}$
\end_inset

 are arbitrary mutually commuting observables, 
\begin_inset Formula $[\psi_{i}]\in[\mathcal{H}]$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\hat{\mathcal{H}}^{\otimes N}\to\mathcal{\hat{H}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $[\psi_{k+1}]\equiv s(\hat{B}_{k},[\psi_{k}],m(\hat{B}_{k},[\psi_{k}]))$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall\,[\psi_{1}]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now discuss the `proofs of contextuality' in the purview of the aforesaid.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
Let a map 
\begin_inset Formula $m:\hat{\mathcal{H}}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, be s.t.
 (a) 
\begin_inset Formula $m(\hat{\mathbb{I}})=1$
\end_inset

, (b) 
\begin_inset Formula $m(f(\hat{A}_{1},\hat{A}_{2},\dots))=f(m(\hat{A}_{1}),m(\hat{A}_{2}),\dots)$
\end_inset

, for any arbitrary function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}_{i}$
\end_inset

 are arbitrary Hermitian operators.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is assumed to describe the outcomes of measurements, then no 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 exists which is consistent with all predictions of Quantum Mechanics.
\end_layout

