\begin_inset Formula $e:\hat{\mathcal{H}}\to\mathcal{E}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
To describe an experimental setup corresponding to a measurement, we use
 a measuring particle (mass 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{L}$
\end_inset

, say).
 It is made to interact with the system for a short duration appropriately
 and subsequently we measure the resultant position of the particle, to
 learn about the value of the observable of interest.
 Say for instance, we wish to measure the observable 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}$
\end_inset

, then the required interaction Hamiltonian is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{H}_{\text{int}}=a\hat{L}\otimes\hat{p}$
\end_inset

.
 Here the first operator acts on the system and second (after the tensor
 product symbol) acts on the measuring particle.
 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 quantifies the interaction strength.
 [TODO: check this] It has dimensions of frequency, if 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 has dimensions of length.
 Let us assume that the system in the state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 Then it is known that one can express 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi\right\rangle =\sum_{l}\left\langle l|\psi\right\rangle \left|l\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|l\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 are the eigenstates of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{L}$
\end_inset

 with eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 (we have assumed non-degeneracy for simplicity, but its removal doesn't
 cause any significant difficulty).
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\Psi_{S}(t)\right\rangle =\hat{U}(t)\left|\psi\right\rangle \otimes\left|\varphi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{U}(t)=e^{-\frac{i}{\hbar}\left[-\hbar^{2}\frac{\nabla_{1}^{2}}{2m}-\hbar^{2}\frac{\nabla_{2}^{2}}{2m_{L}}+\hat{H}_{\text{int}}\right]t}
\]

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\varphi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 is the state of the measuring particle, given by a Guassian centred at
 the origin, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi(q)=(1/\sqrt{2\pi}\sigma)e^{-q^{2}/2\sigma^{2}}$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is very small, and 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 very large, s.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $at=\lambda$
\end_inset

 is a finite number, then one can neglect the free evolution, 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla^{2}t$
\end_inset

 terms compared to 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{H}_{\text{int}}t$
\end_inset

.
 We then have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left|\Psi_{S}(t)\right\rangle  & = & e^{-\frac{i}{\hbar}a\hat{L}\otimes\hat{p}t}\left|\Psi_{S}\right\rangle \\
 & = & \sum_{l}\left\langle l|\psi\right\rangle \left|l\right\rangle \otimes e^{-\frac{i}{\hbar}\lambda l\,\hat{p}}\left|\varphi\right\rangle \\
 & = & \sum_{l}\left\langle l|\psi\right\rangle \left|l\right\rangle \otimes\left|\varphi_{\lambda l}\right\rangle ,
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\varphi_{q_{0}}\right\rangle =\int dq\varphi(q-q_{0})\left|q\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 This interaction, effectively entangles the measuring particle, with the
